Classification

Dr.Â Liu Qizhang

1 November 2016

In previous lesson, you learned how to predict a categorical outcome using logistic regression. The process of predicting a categorical outcome from a set of predictors is called Classification, which is part of pattern recognition. Other than logistic regression, decision trees, random forests, support vector machines, and neural networks are some common methods used in classification. We will mainly discuss Naive Bayes, decision trees and random forests in this lesson.

Naive Bayes Classification

Naive Bayes is a simplified version of Bayesâ Theorem by assuming all predictors are independent from each other. For an explanation of Naive Bayes Classification, please refer to http://stackoverflow.com/questions/10059594/a-simple-explanation-of-naive-bayes-classification.

I am going to use Lasagna Trier data to illustrate how to use it.

triers <- read.csv("Lasagna Triers.csv")
triers$Person <- NULL
set.seed(123)
sample <- sample(c(TRUE,FALSE),nrow(triers),prob = c(0.75,0.25),replace = TRUE)

triers.train <- triers[sample, ]
triers.test <- triers[!sample, ]

Assume that we are going to use three predictors: Age, PayType, and Nbhd to predict whether a customer will be trier of the product. Then the probability of a customer with profle age 30, living in the west and working as part timer to be a trier will be calculated using the formula below:

p(Yes|Age=30,PayType=âHourlyâ,Nbhd=âWestâ) =P(Age=30|Yes)P(PayType=âHourlyâ|Yes)P(Nbhd=âWestâ|Yes)P(Yes) / [P(Age=30|Yes)P(PayType=âHourlyâ|Yes)P(Nbhd=âWestâ|Yes)P(Yes) + P(Age=30|No)P(PayType=âHourlyâ|No)P(Nbhd=âWestâ|No)P(No)]

It is quite easy to calculate P(Yes) and P(No).

p.yes <- nrow(triers.train[triers.train$HaveTried=="Yes",])/nrow(triers.train)
p.no <- nrow(triers.train[triers.train$HaveTried=="No",])/nrow(triers.train)
p.yes
## [1] 0.5990712
p.no
## [1] 0.4009288

For categorical predictor, it is also quite easy to calcualte the conditional probabilities. For example:

p.West.Given.Yes <- nrow(triers.train[triers.train$HaveTried=="Yes"&triers.train$Nbhd=="West",])/nrow(triers.train[triers.train$HaveTried=="Yes",])
p.West.Given.Yes
## [1] 0.5994832

However, it will be a bit difficult for numerical predictors. There are two ways to handle numerical predictors. One way is to break the numerical values into categories according to some predefined thresholds, and then use the resulted categories as categorical predictor to calculate the posterior probability. For example, we may classify those with age below 30 as young and those above as senior. The problem with this approach is that the accuracy of the prediction depends very much on how the numercial values are classified.

Another approach is to use the probability distribution of the numerical predictor under different scenarios. Letâs take a look at the probability distributions of Age for the case of triers and nontriers respectively.

library(ggplot2)
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.3.2
ggplot(triers,aes(x=Age,color=HaveTried)) + geom_density()

The plot shows that both ages of triers and ages of nontriers are following bell shape. We can further use shapiro-Wilk test to validate.

shapiro.test(triers[triers$HaveTried=="Yes",]$Age)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  triers[triers$HaveTried == "Yes", ]$Age
## W = 0.94679, p-value = 2.431e-12
shapiro.test(triers[triers$HaveTried=="No",]$Age)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  triers[triers$HaveTried == "No", ]$Age
## W = 0.98155, p-value = 0.0001412

Both test validate that the ages for the two groups follow normal distribution. Then we should do is to use the attributesâ mean and standard deviation, for each of the two class outcomes (HaveTried=Yes and HaveTried=No), we estimate the pdf value at any given decision point and use it as the conditional probability in the formula.

#Find the mean and standard deviation of ages for triers
mean.triers <- mean(triers.train[triers.train$HaveTried=="Yes",]$Age)
sd.triers <- sd(triers.train[triers.train$HaveTried=="Yes",]$Age)

#Find the mean and standard deviation of ages for nontriers
mean.nontriers <- mean(triers.train[triers.train$HaveTried=="No",]$Age)
sd.nontriers <- sd(triers.train[triers.train$HaveTried=="No",]$Age)

#Example: find the conditional probability of p(Age=30 | Yes)
dnorm(30,mean.triers,sd.triers)
## [1] 0.03618302

Based on the method of calculating prior probability and conditional probability, it is not difficult to write a procedure to calculate posterior probability using the Naive Bayes formula. I will leave this for you to try yourself.

require(e1071)
## Loading required package: e1071
## Warning: package 'e1071' was built under R version 3.3.2
#Build model using training set
m <- naiveBayes(HaveTried ~ ., data = triers.train)

#use the model to predict outcomes for test set
a<-table(predict(m, triers.train), triers.train$HaveTried)
accuracy <- (a[1,1]+a[2,2])/sum(a)
accuracy
## [1] 0.8080495

We need to re-format the data for our analysis.

#Convert "Default" field as factor
credit$Default <- factor(credit$Default)

#Re-level some variables
credit$history = factor(credit$history, levels=c("A30","A31","A32","A33","A34"))
levels(credit$history) = c("good","good","poor","poor","terrible")

credit$foreign <- factor(credit$foreign, levels=c("A201","A202"),labels=c("foreign","german"))

credit$purpose <- factor(credit$purpose, levels=c("A40","A41","A42","A43","A44","A45","A46","A47","A48","A49","A410"))
levels(credit$purpose) <- c("newcar","usedcar",rep("goods/repair",4), "edu",NA, "edu","biz","biz")

#Introduce a new variable to indicate if the applicant is renting a house
credit$rent <- factor(credit$housing=="A151")

Decision tree is a technique that separate observations into subgroups by creating splits on predictors. These split create logical rules that are transparent and easily understandable. The resulting subgroups should be more homogenous in terms of the outcome variable, thereby creating useful prediction or classification rules. We will look into two types of decision trees: classical trees and conditional inference trees.

Classical decision trees

The following steps illustrate the procedure of spliting observations on predictors:

  1. Choose the predictor variable that best splits the data into two groups suc that the purity (homogeneity) of the outcome in these two groups is maximized. If the predictor is continuous, choose a cut-point that maximizes purity for the two groups created. If the predictor variable is categorical, combine the categories to obtain two groups with maximum purity.

  2. Separate the data into these two groups, and continue the process for each subgroup.

  3. Repeat step 1 and 2 until a subgroup contains fewer tha a minimum number of observations or no splits decrease the impurity beyond a specific threshold. The subgroups in the final set are called terminal nodes. Each terminal node is classified as one category of the outcome or the other based on the most frequent value of the outcome for the sample in that node.

  4. To classify a case, run it down the tree to a terminal node, and assign it the modal outcome value asigned in step 3.

Splitting - explanaton of step 1

Now letâs use German Credit data to demonstrate how a data set is split and how purity is measured.

#First understand the distribution of default and non-default cases
table(credit$Default)
## 
##   0   1 
## 700 300
#Next, see the distribution by "foreign"
df.foreign <- as.data.frame.matrix(table(credit$foreign, credit$Default))
df.foreign$default.rate <- df.foreign[,2]/(df.foreign[,1]+df.foreign[,2])
df.foreign
##           0   1 default.rate
## foreign 667 296    0.3073728
## german   33   4    0.1081081
#See the distribution by "history"
df.history <- as.data.frame.matrix(table(credit$history, credit$Default))
df.history$default.rate <- df.history[,2]/(df.history[,1]+df.history[,2])
df.history
##            0   1 default.rate
## good      36  53    0.5955056
## poor     421 197    0.3187702
## terrible 243  50    0.1706485

Use different categorical predictor will result in different purity. There are also different ways to measure and compare overall purity in different decision tree algorithms. For example, some will compare by the higher purity of the two groups, some will compare by average purity of the two groups, and some will compare by weighted average of the two groups. We may split by âhistoryâ and classify those with âgoodâ history as one group and those with âpoorâ and âterribleâ as another group.

Decision Tree Function

The normal decision tree procedure as described above tends to produce a tree with too many terminal nodes and thus suffers from overfitting. You may have to prune the tree by choosing the tree with the lowest 10-fold cross-validated prediction error.

Letâs apply the decision tree classification method on German credit data again. We start with a general purpose classification, which is to minimize the misclassification error.

library(rpart)
set.seed(1234)
sample <- sample(c(TRUE,FALSE),nrow(credit),prob = c(0.8,0.2),replace = TRUE)
credit.train <- credit[sample, ]
credit.test <- credit[!sample, ]

dtree <- rpart(Default ~ ., data=credit.train, method="class", parms=list(split="information"))
summary(dtree)

summary, print and prp are the functions to view the details of the classification. As you can see, there seems to have too many terminal nodes. We can examine the cptable component of the list returned by rpart() and determine the best size of the tree.

dtree$cptable
##           CP nsplit rel error    xerror       xstd
## 1 0.04424779      0 1.0000000 1.0000000 0.05623302
## 2 0.03539823      3 0.8407080 0.9203540 0.05479830
## 3 0.01991150      4 0.8053097 0.9115044 0.05462751
## 4 0.01327434      6 0.7654867 0.8982301 0.05436691
## 5 0.01032448     10 0.7123894 0.8893805 0.05419020
## 6 0.01000000     13 0.6814159 0.8893805 0.05419020
plotcp(dtree)

A tree with n splits has n+1 terminal nodes. The rel error column contains the error rate for a tree of a given size in the training smaple. The cross validated error xerror is based on 10-fold cross validation. The xstd column contains the standard error of the cross-validation error. The complexity parameter cp is used to penalise large trees. Tree size is defined by the number of branch splits nsplit. The plotcp() function plots the cross-validated error against the complexity parameter. A good choice for the final tree size is the smallest tree whose cross-validated error is within one standard error of the minimum cross-validated error value.

The output from cptable shows an undesirable result. The minimum cross-validated error happens when there is no split, which means a naive classification by classifying all cases as no-default appears to be a good prediction.

dtree.pruned <- prune(dtree, cp=0.023)
prp(dtree.pruned, type=2, extra=104, fallen.leaves = TRUE, main="Decision Tree")

dtree.pred <- predict(dtree.pruned, credit.test, type="class")
accuracy <- table(credit.test$Default, dtree.pred,dnn=c("Actual","Predicted"))
accuracy
##       Predicted
## Actual   0   1
##      0 118  16
##      1  40  34

You can adjust the prune criteria by lowering the cp value. What is the effect? How to interpret it?

One thing you may have observed is that the model above did not take the cost of mis-classification into consideration. You can use loss= to specify the cost matrix.

set.seed(1234)
dtree <- rpart(Default ~ ., data=credit.train, method="class", parms=list(split="information",loss=matrix(c(0,1,5,0), byrow=TRUE, nrow=2)))
dtree$cptable

Conditional Inference Trees

Cnoditional inference trees are similar to classical decision trees, but variables and splits are selected based on significance tests rather than purity/homogeneity measures.

library(grid)
library(mvtnorm)
library(modeltools)
## Loading required package: stats4
library(stats4)
library(strucchange)

## 
##     as.Date, as.Date.numeric
## Loading required package: sandwich
library(zoo)
library(party)
## Warning: package 'party' was built under R version 3.3.2
fit.ctree <- ctree(Default ~ ., data=credit.train)
plot(fit.ctree, main="Conditional inference tree")

ctree.pred <- predict(fit.ctree, credit.test, type="response")
accuracy <- table(credit.test$Default, ctree.pred,dnn=c("Actual","Predicted"))
accuracy
##       Predicted
## Actual   0   1
##      0 118  16
##      1  40  34

The result shows a better overall error rate than classical decision tree. But again, the result did not take the cost into consideration. We can modify the codes to set different weights to the misclassification cases.

fit.ctree <- ctree(Default ~ ., data=credit.train, weights = ifelse(credit.train$Default=="0",1,5))
plot(fit.ctree, main="Conditional inference tree")

ctree.pred <- predict(fit.ctree, credit.test, type="response")
accuracy <- table(credit.test$Default, ctree.pred,dnn=c("Actual","Predicted"))
accuracy
##       Predicted
## Actual  0  1
##      0 89 45
##      1 20 54

Random Forests

Random Forests is an ensemble learning method for classification, regression and other tasks, that operate by constructing a multitude of decision trees at training time and outputting the class that is the mode of the classes (classification) or mean prediction (regression) of the individual trees. Random decision forests correct for decision treesâ habit of overfitting to their training set.

The algorithm of random forests works like the following:

  • Grow a large number of decision trees by sampling N cases with replacement from the training set.
  • Sample m<N variables at each node. These variables are considered candidates for splitting in that node. The value m is the same for each node.
  • Grow each tree fully without pruning.
  • Terminal nodes are assigned to a class based on the mode of cases in that node.
  • Classify new cases by sending them down all the trees and taking a vote - majority rules.

The following codes shows how to run random forests on the credit data set.

library(randomForest)
## randomForest 4.6-12
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
## 
## Attaching package: 'randomForest'
## The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     margin
set.seed(1234)

fit.forest <- randomForest(Default ~., data=credit.train, na.action = na.roughfix,importance=TRUE, cutoff=c(.85,.15))
importance(fit.forest, type=2)

The cutoff parameter in the above codes is the way to handle the asymmetric costs. If the costs are not asymmetric, then you may just exclude this parameter from the function.
